M|7.8 |**Im|md-hi (avoids expensive operations when lengths differ)**
M|7.8 |tx|When comparing arrays w/ expensive operations (sorting, deep equality, serialization), check lengths first. If lengths differ, the arrays cannot be equal.
M|7.8 |tx|In real-world applications, this op is esp valuable when the comparison runs in hot paths (event handlers, render loops).
M|7.8 |**In|always runs expensive comparison**
M|7.8 |tx|```ts
M|7.8 |func|string[], original: string[]) {
M|7.8 |tx|// Always sorts and joins, even when lengths differ
M|7.8 |tx|return current.sort().join() !== original.sort().join()
M|7.8 |tx|}
M|7.8 |tx|```
M|7.8 |tx|Two O(n log n) sorts run even when `current.length` is 5 and `original.length` is 100. There is also overhead of joining the arrays and comparing the strings.
M|7.8 |**Co|**
M|7.8 |tx|```ts
M|7.8 |func|string[], original: string[]) {
M|7.8 |tx|// Early return if lengths differ
M|7.8 |tx|if (current.length !== original.length) {
M|7.8 |tx|return true
M|7.8 |tx|}
M|7.8 |tx|// Only sort when lengths match
M|7.8 |tx|const currentSorted = current.toSorted()
M|7.8 |tx|const originalSorted = original.toSorted()
M|7.8 |tx|for (let i = 0; i < currentSorted.length; i++) {
M|7.8 |tx|if (currentSorted[i] !== originalSorted[i]) {
M|7.8 |tx|return true
M|7.8 |tx|}
M|7.8 |tx|}
M|7.8 |tx|return false
M|7.8 |tx|}
M|7.8 |tx|```
M|7.8 |This|
M|7.8 |it|It avoids the overhead of sorting and joining the arrays when lengths differ
M|7.8 |it|It avoids consuming memory for the joined strings (esp important for large arrays)
M|7.8 |it|It avoids mutating the original arrays
M|7.8 |it|It returns early when a difference is found
M|7.9 |**Im|lo-md (avoids unnecessary computation)**
M|7.9 |tx|Return early when result is determined to skip unnecessary processing.
M|7.9 |**In|processes all items even after finding answer**
