M|7.12|**Im|lo (O(n) instead of O(n log n))**
M|7.12|tx|Finding the smallest or largest element only requires a single pass through the array. Sorting is wasteful and slower.
M|7.12|**In|**
M|7.12|tx|```ts
M|7.12|tx|if Project {
M|7.12|id|string
M|7.12|name|string
M|7.12|upda|number
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|func|Project[]) {
M|7.12|tx|const sorted = [...projects].sort((a, b) => b.updatedAt - a.updatedAt)
M|7.12|tx|return sorted[0]
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|tx|```
M|7.12|tx|Sorts the entire array just to find the maximum value.
M|7.12|**In|**
M|7.12|tx|```ts
M|7.12|func|Project[]) {
M|7.12|tx|const sorted = [...projects].sort((a, b) => a.updatedAt - b.updatedAt)
M|7.12|retu|sorted[0], newest: sorted[sorted.length - 1] }
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|tx|```
M|7.12|tx|Still sorts unnecessarily when only min/max are needed.
M|7.12|**Co|**
M|7.12|tx|```ts
M|7.12|func|Project[]) {
M|7.12|tx|if (projects.length === 0) return null
M|7.12|tx|let latest = projects[0]
M|7.12|tx|for (let i = 1; i < projects.length; i++) {
M|7.12|tx|if (projects[i].updatedAt > latest.updatedAt) {
M|7.12|tx|latest = projects[i]
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|tx|return latest
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|func|Project[]) {
M|7.12|if (|null, newest: null }
M|7.12|tx|let oldest = projects[0]
M|7.12|tx|let newest = projects[0]
M|7.12|tx|for (let i = 1; i < projects.length; i++) {
M|7.12|tx|if (projects[i].updatedAt < oldest.updatedAt) oldest = projects[i]
M|7.12|tx|if (projects[i].updatedAt > newest.updatedAt) newest = projects[i]
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|tx|return { oldest, newest }
M|7.12|tx|}
M|7.12|tx|```
M|7.12|tx|Single pass through the array, no copying, no sorting.
M|7.12|**Al|Math.min/Math.max for small arrays**
M|7.12|tx|```ts
M|7.12|tx|const numbers = [5, 2, 8, 1, 9]
M|7.12|tx|const min = Math.min(...numbers)
M|7.12|tx|const max = Math.max(...numbers)
M|7.12|tx|```
