M|7.14|**Im|md-hi (prevents mutation bugs in rc state)**
M|7.14|tx|`.sort()` mutates the array in place, which can cause bugs w/ rc state and props. Use `.toSorted()` to cr a new sorted array w/o mutation.
M|7.14|**In|mutates original array**
M|7.14|tx|```ts
M|7.14|func|{ us: us[] }) {
M|7.14|tx|// Mutates the us prop array!
M|7.14|tx|const sorted = useMemo(
M|7.14|tx|() => us.sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)),
M|7.14|tx|[us]
M|7.14|tx|)
M|7.14|tx|return <div>{sorted.map(renderUser)}</div>
M|7.14|tx|}
M|7.14|tx|```
M|7.14|**Co|creates new array**
M|7.14|tx|```ts
M|7.14|func|{ us: us[] }) {
M|7.14|tx|// Creates new sorted array, original unchanged
M|7.14|tx|const sorted = useMemo(
M|7.14|tx|() => us.toSorted((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)),
M|7.14|tx|[us]
M|7.14|tx|)
M|7.14|tx|return <div>{sorted.map(renderUser)}</div>
M|7.14|tx|}
M|7.14|tx|```
M|7.14|**Wh|**
M|7.14|tx|1. Props/state mutations break rc's immutability md - rc expects props and state to be treated as read-only
M|7.14|tx|2. Causes stale closure bugs - Mutating arrays inside closures (callbacks, effects) can lead to unexpected behavior
M|7.14|**Br|fallback for older browsers**
M|7.14|tx|```ts
M|7.14|tx|// Fallback for older browsers
M|7.14|tx|const sorted = [...items].sort((a, b) => a.value - b.value)
M|7.14|tx|```
M|7.14|`.to|
M|7.14|**Ot|**
M|7.14|it|`.toSorted()` - immutable sort
M|7.14|it|`.toReversed()` - immutable reverse
M|7.14|it|`.toSpliced()` - immutable splice
M|7.14|it|`.w/()` - immutable element replacement
